Chemical Hazards

Toxicologically, methane is classified as a simple asphyxiant.  The routes of exposure are inhalation and dermal contact.  Methane is inactive biologically and essentially nontoxic.  Therefore, the major properties are the exclusion of an adequate supply of oxygen to the lungs; effects are dizziness, unconsciousness, and eventual collapse.  Skin contact with the LNG or cold piping can cause freezing or frostbite.

The main hazards associated with LNG are fire and explosion.  The flash point of methane is ?306 degrees Fahrenheit (closed cup), the lower flammability limit is 5 percent, and the upper flammability limit is 
15 percent.

Prevention Program

The LNG covered process is subject to Program 3 prevention program requirements because it is subject to OSHA?s PSM standards and is not eligible for Program 1.  The PG&E Program 3 prevention program includes the following:
?Process Safety Information;
?Process Hazard Review;
?Operating Procedures;
?Training;
?Mechanical Integrity;
?Management of Change;
?Pre-Startup Safety Review;
?Compliance Audits;
?Incident Investigations;
?Employee Participation;
?Hot Work Permit; and
?Contractors.

Five-Year Accident History

The LNG Facility is a demonstration project and, as such, there have been no CalARP RMP reportable releases at the LNG Facility in the past 5 years that resulted in either of the following:
?On-site deaths, injuries, or significant property damage; or
?Known off-site deaths, injuries, property damage, environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place.

